“Coments: This description matches two undescribed, oak-associated, yellow capped Russula with ochre-orange mature gills, white stipes, and a mild taste; we have yet to find any macro-morphological differences between them. The dark ochre spores alone help distinguish them from similar Russula. R. basifurcata has a whitish to creamy buff cap that becomes yellow and often develops pink tones around the margin. It also has cream to pale yellow gills that are fused and/or forked near the stipe, pale yellow spores, and a mild to slightly bitter taste. R. chamaeleotina has a pink to rose-colored when young (often with a whitish disc), becoming salmon pink with a yellowish orange disc in age. It has creamy yellow to ochre gills and a mild taste.
